  "doc_id": "14317",
  "text": "It is notable that there are both similarities and disparities between the phenotypes of XBP1 and IRE1 knock out mice. At the molecular level, Ern1 deletion abolishes the expression of both IRE1 and XBP1s. In contrast, Xbp1 de letion abolishes the expression of XBP1u and XBP1s, but activates IRE1 in certain organs and cell types, such as liver, intestinal epithelium,  cells, and macrophages; however, XBP1 does not activate IRE1 in neurons. Germ line dele tion of Ern1 or Xbp1 caused embryonic lethality in mice because of impaired liver development [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Interestingly, the embryonic lethal phe notypes of these mice were reversed by expression of IRE1 in the placenta or XBP1 in the liver [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , indicating differential requirements for IRE1 and XBP1 in the development of these organs. XBP1 and IRE1deficient mice display abnormalities in secretory cells and organs, but the latter appear to have milder pheno types [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . One exception to this, however, is in the B cell lineage, where IRE1deficient chimeras display a halt in B cell differ entiation at an early stage of B cell development [CITATION_8] in contrast to XBP1 lymphoid chimeras or B cell-specific Xbp1 f/f ;CD19 +/cre mice where B cell development proceeds normally until the terminal stage of B cell differentiation to plasma cells [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . It remains to be determined if this difference in timing and se verity of phenotype is caused by a contribution by RIDD or can be explained by different experimental settings, such as mouse genetic background.",
